"Linux Kernel": "The Linux Kernel is the core component of the Linux operating system. It is responsible for managing the system's resources, including memory, processors, and input/output devices. The kernel handles system calls, manages hardware devices, and provides a layer of abstraction between the hardware and the rest of the operating system. It is responsible for enabling the system to run multiple applications simultaneously, providing a secure and stable environment for those applications to run in. The Linux Kernel is open-source software, meaning that its source code is freely available for anyone to view, modify, and distribute."
